Unlithified, skeletal grainstone with coarse sand to granule size grains. Bioclasts include bivalves, gastropods. Lithoclasts include carbonate and glauconite.

Lithified, cream, skeletal packstone with sand to coarse sand size grains and with foraminfers. Bioclasts up to 3 cm long and include bryozoans and bivalves. Grains include carbonate and less glauconite than in previously described cores

This core includes at least three different lithologies that were likely mixed during coring. All three lithologies have dolomite cement. From top to bottom: Lithified, cream, light greenish gray, skeletal grainstone with sand, coarse sand and up to large pebble size bioclasts and lithoclasts. The lithoclasts include glauconite decreasing in abundance down core and carbonate grains. The bioclasts include benthic forams and bivalve. Lithoclasts include abundant glauconite. A coarser grained, creamy gray grainstone containing benthic forams, cycloclypeous and bivalves. Abundant solution cavities and moldic porosity Containing some glauconite A cream packstone include bivalve fragments 2x3 cm thick and long. The supporting matrix are benthic foram, cycloclypeous, bivalve fragments and bryozoan. Abundant solution cavities and moldic porosity and very sparse glauconite.

Lithified, creamy gray, skeletal packstone with foraminfers and sand to coarse sand size grains. The bioclasts: abundant bentic forams and bivalves (up to 2 cm long), small amount of bryozoan. Lithified, skeletal, creamy gray grainstone with sand to coarse sand size grains. Lithoclasts include sparse glauconite and common carbonate grains. Bioclasts fragments up to 3 cm long include bivalves, bryozoa. Occasional dark greenish gray bivalve fragment heavily bioeroded

Lithified, skeletal brown dolostone, likely a solution surface with common solution cavities and moldic porosity, molds of colonial reef building corals. Bioclasts include benthic forams, bryozoa, bivalve fragments.

Lithified, dark brown, very fine grained dolostone with common solution cavities and moldic porosity. Bioclasts include coral fragments? Bivalves and gastropods and sea urchin spine. Most shells have dissolved and only moldic porosity remains

Lithified, skeletal, light brown packstone with sand to coarse sand size grains. Some bioclasts and matrix replaced by gypsum and/or dolomite. Bioclasts present include bryozoan, bivalves, gastropod (a large one 5 cm across and the shell replaced by gypsum), a solitary coral.

Lithified, creamy gray dolostone with some sand size gypsum grains. Sand size shell fragments (not identified) sparse forams

These beds at 43-54 cm, 103-105 and 120-124 cm have sharp basal and top contacts. LIthified, light brown dolomitic grainstone with fine sand size grains and several intervals of coarse grained material between 62-74 cm. The base is sharp the upper contact is gradational. It includes glauconite, coarse sand size grains and macrofossils abundant forams, including cycloclypeus, fragments of bryozoan. There is slight bioturbation noted by dark brown patches. Bivalve shells are noted by dark brown likely replacemet by gypsum.

Lithified, light brown dolomitic grainstone with sand size grains. Beds of coarse sand to granule size grains, light greenish gray and composed of litho and bioclasts are present throughout the Section. The beds have sharp lower contacts and gradational upper contacts. Beds are between 29-35 cm, 44-84 cm, 102-11 cm, 114-119 cm. Burrows infilled with coarse sand size grains between 84-96 cm. Bioclasts are mainly composed of benthic forams, bryozoan fragments, urchin spines. Lithic grains are mainly composed of glauconite. The sand size grainstone contains slight bioturbation and burrows replaced by dark brown material (grypsum?)

Lithified, light brown dolomitic grainstone with sand size grains. Slight bioturbation, burrows and shells have been replaced with gypsum? (dark brown to black). The grainstone has brown intervals that contain parallel laminae. There is one coarse sand size grained bed from 10-13 cm. Grains are green/black possibly glauconite and/or pyrite. Macrofossils are mainly forams with bryozoan and occasional bivalve fragments. Moldic porosity towards the base of the core.

Lithified, brown dolomitic grainstone with coarse sand size grains with abundant macrofossils and lithoclasts. Anhydrite nodules up to 5 cm long and with chicken wire texture are in between 35 to 39 cm. Glauconite forming in shell cavities,as granules, and infilling burrows common (21-27 cm) and sparse throughout the Section. Very faint laminations present between 12-15 cm and noted by dark brown. Moldic porosity common. Small (few mm's) burrows and shells infilled with brown and blacks mineral (could be gypsum). Macrofossils include corals, cycloclypeus foraminfer abudnant, encrusting coral (montipora?) solitary coral and massive coral plerogyra? Abundant shell fragments including bryozans, urchin spines, coraline algae

LIthified, light brown and dark brown dolomitic grainstone with fine sand size grains and coarse sand size grains between 6-19 cm. Common moldic porosity. Glauconite grains and glauconite in burrows also common. Gypsum and/or brown-black mineral replacing shells. Macrofossils include abundant forams, bryozoan fragments and occasional bivalve fragments

LIthfied, light brown and brown dolomitic wackestone with fine sand and sand size grains. Abundant burrows? a few mm's long infilled with brown material (likely gypsume) Glauconite grains also common. Macrofossils are mainly benthic foraminifers, bryozan and bivalve fragments

LIthified, light brown and brown dolomitic wackestone with very fine sand size grains and common bioturbation. Burrows are large a few cm's thick and at up to 5 cm long and brown. Abundant mm-scale brown (possibly infilled with gypsum) burrows? are common throughout the Section. Recognizable benthic forams, sparse bryozoan and bivalve shell fragments (most are unidentifiable)

LIthified, light brown and brown wackestone with very fine sand size grains and common bioturbation. Burrows are large a few cm's thick and at up to 5 cm long and brown. Abundant mm-scale brown (possibly infilled with gypsum) burrows? are common throughout the Section. Parallel lamianations (133 -140 cm) and load cast at 117 cm. Benthic forams in burrows, sparse bryozoan and bivalve shell fragments (most are unidentifiable). A gypsum nodule several mm's long infills a shell at 60-61 cm

Lithified, light brownish gray wackestone with sand size grains and slight bioturbation. Glauconite sand size grains common. Bioturbation is slight. Small (mm long) burrows infilled with brown material (possibly gypsume). Macrofossils include abundant forams, large bryozoan and small bryozoan fragments, and sparse bivalve fragments. Macros throughout the Section

Lithified, light brown and brown packstone with sand size grains. There are abundant glauconite grains. At 34 ad 44 cm sharp sub-horizontal contacts with coarser sand size grains and glauconite replacement of shells. The macros above include large forams and possibly bivalves. Macros include benthic foraminiers and bryozoan shell fragments. Small (mm long) burrows are replaced with brown infill (possibly gypsume)

Lithified,light gray to light brown grainstone with coarse sand size grains and higher porosity. Glauconite grains common. Macrofossils abundant: benthic forams including cycloclypeus and bryozoan. Sparse bivalve fragments. The grainstone is dark brown towards the base (63-69 cm). Gypsum replacement of shells (mm sacle) and grains replaced by bright grayish blue mineral (anhydrite?)

Lithified,light gray to light brown grainstone with coarse sand size grains and higher porosity. Glauconite grains common. Macrofossils abundant: benthic forams including cycloclypeus and bryozoan. Sparse bivalve fragments. The grainstone is dark brown towards the base (63-69 cm). Gypsum replacement of shells (mm sacle) and grains replaced by bright grayish blue mineral (anhydrite?)

Lithified, light brown grainstone with sand and coarse sand size grains. Common bioturbation and common burrows noted by dark brown color. Laminated and possibly thin bedded intervals noted by dark brown more common towards the base of the Section. Macrofossils are abundant forams including cylcoclypeous, and ,shell fragments of bryozan and bivalves. Light bluish gray concretions up to 4 cm thick and 5 cm wide composed of nodule like features In the upper 20 cm of the Section. They could possibly be anhydrite? Gypsum more common towards the base of the Section

Lithified, light brown grainstone with sand and coarse sand size grains. Common bioturbation and common burrows noted by dark brown color. Laminated and possibly thin bedded intervals noted by dark brown more common towards the top and base of the Section. Macrofossils are abundant forams including cylcoclypeous, and shell fragments of bryozan and bivalves. Light bluish gray nodules and as shell replacement are common (possibly anhydrite). Moldic porosity as small cavities. Some filled with bluish materila. Gypsum more common towards the top and base of the Section

Lithified, light brown packstone with sand size grains. Slight bioturbation and sparse burrows noted by dark brown color. Laminated and possibly thin bedded intervals noted by dark brown between 11-18 cm. This interval also contains light grayish blue material as shell replacement. Macrofossils are abundant forams including cylcoclypeous, and fragments of bryozan, bivalves and one gastropod. Shells are mainly white in most of the Section except near the top when some are brown and possibly replaced by gypsum.

LIthified, light greenish gray packstone with sand size grains and with glauconite. Macros include benthic foraminfers, cycloclypeus not as abundant, bryozans, bivalves and gastropod molds. Some burrows infilled with light bluish gray mineral.
